GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 799
Short Title: Ensure Nondiscrimination in Government. (Public)
Sponsors: Representatives Echevarria, Setzer, and Gable (Primary Sponsors).
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Rules, Calendar, and Operations of the House
April 8, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO ENSURE NONDISCRIMINATION AND DIGNITY IN GOVERNMENT
3 HIRING, PROMOTION, TRAINING, AND WORKPLACES.
4 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
5 SECTION 1.(a) G.S. 126-14.6 reads as rewritten:
6 "§ 126-14.6. Ensuring dignity and nondiscrimination in State government workplaces.
7 (a) The General Assembly finds that Article I, Section 1 of the Constitution of this State
8 recognizes the equality and rights of all persons. Therefore, it is the intent of the General
9 Assembly that State employees respect the dignity of others, acknowledge the right of others to
10 express differing opinions, and the right to freedom of speech and association and that State
11 agencies employ training methods and procedures to further that intent. Further, it is the public
12 policy of this State that State employee hiring, promotion, and training shall be without regard to
13 race or ethnicity, religion, or sex and that applications for State employment shall not inquire
14 about race.
15 (b) For the purposes of this section, "promote" shall mean compelling State employees
16 or contractors to affirm or profess belief in the concepts described in subsection (c) of this section.
17 (c) The concepts listed in this subsection shall not be promoted in State government
18 workplaces or included as part of any State employee training program:
19 (1) One race or sex is inherently superior to another race or sex.
20 (2) An individual, solely by virtue of his or her race or sex, is inherently racist,
21 sexist, or oppressive.
22 (3) An individual should be discriminated against or receive adverse treatment
23 solely or partly because of his or her race or sex.
24 (4) An individual's moral character is necessarily determined by his or her race or
25 sex.
26 (5) An individual, solely by virtue of his or her race or sex, bears responsibility
27 for actions committed in the past by other members of the same race or sex.
28 (6) Any individual, solely by virtue of his or her race or sex, should feel
29 discomfort, guilt, anguish, or any other form of psychological distress.
30 (7) A meritocracy is inherently racist or sexist.
31 (8) The United States was created by members of a particular race or sex for the
32 purpose of oppressing members of another race or sex.
33 (9) The United States government should be violently overthrown.
*H799-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (10) Particular character traits, values, moral or ethical codes, privileges, or beliefs
2 should be ascribed to a race or sex or to an individual because of the
3 individual's race or sex.
4 (11) The rule of law does not exist, but instead is a series of power relationships
5 and struggles among racial or other groups.
6 (12) All Americans are not created equal and are not endowed by their Creator with
7 certain unalienable rights, including life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness.
8 (13) Governments should deny to any person within the government's jurisdiction
9 the equal protection of the law.
10 (c) The concepts listed in this subsection shall not be promoted in State government
11 workplaces or included as part of any State employee training program, to wit that: one race,
12 religion, ethnicity, or sex is inherently superior to another race, religion, ethnicity, or sex; an
13 individual, solely by virtue of his or her race, religion, ethnicity, or sex, is inherently racist, sexist,
14 oppressive, or inherently victimized; an individual should be discriminated against, receive
15 adverse treatment, or receive favored treatment solely or partly because of his or her race,
16 religion, ethnicity, or sex; an individual's moral character is necessarily determined by his or her
17 race, religion, ethnicity, or sex; an individual, solely by virtue of his or her race, religion,
18 ethnicity, or sex, bears responsibility for actions committed in the past by other members of the
19 same race, religion, ethnicity, or sex; any individual, solely by virtue of his or her race, religion,
20 ethnicity, or sex, should feel entitlement or feel discomfort, guilt, anguish, or any other form of
21 psychological distress; a meritocracy is inherently racist or sexist; the United States was created
22 by members of a particular race, religion, ethnicity, or sex for the purpose of oppressing members
23 of another race, religion, ethnicity, or sex; the United States government should be violently
24 overthrown; particular character traits, values, moral or ethical codes, privileges, or beliefs
25 should be ascribed to a race, religion, ethnicity, or sex or to an individual because of the
26 individual's race, religion, ethnicity, or sex; the rule of law does not exist but instead is a series
27 of power relationships and struggles among racial, religious, ethnic, or other groups; all
28 Americans are not created equal and are not endowed by their Creator with certain unalienable
29 rights, including life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness; and governments should deny to any
30 person within the government's jurisdiction the equal protection of the law.
31 (d) Nothing in this section prevents a private contractor who provides training to State
32 employees from responding to questions that are raised by participants in the training and which
33 pertain to the concepts in subsection (c) of this section. However, the private contractor must
34 make it clear that the government employer does not endorse those concepts.
35 (e) This section does not apply to speech protected by the First Amendment of the U.S.
36 Constitution.
37 (f) A violation of this section constitutes employment discrimination."
38 SECTION 1.(b) G.S. 126-34.02(b) reads as rewritten:
39 "(b) The following issues may be heard as contested cases after completion of the agency
40 grievance procedure and the Office of State Human Resources review:
41 (1) Discrimination or harassment. – An applicant for State employment, a State
42 employee, or former State employee may allege discrimination or harassment
43 based on race, religion, color, ethnicity, national origin, sex, age, disability,
44 genetic information, or political affiliation if the employee believes that he or
45 she has been discriminated against in his or her application for employment
46 or in the terms and conditions of the employee's employment, or in the
47 termination of his or her employment. A violation of G.S. 126-14.6 constitutes
48 employment discrimination under this subsection.
49 …."
50 SECTION 2. Part 4 of Article 7 of Chapter 160A of the General Statutes is amended
51 by adding the following new sections to read:
Page 2 House Bill 799-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 "§ 160A-170. Compelled speech prohibited.
2 (a) Each city agency and department shall comply with the following:
3 (1) Refrain from soliciting or requiring an applicant for employment to endorse
4 or opine about beliefs, affiliations, ideals, or principles regarding matters of
5 contemporary political debate or social action as a condition of employment.
6 (2) Refrain from soliciting or requiring an applicant for employment to describe
7 the applicant's actions in support of, or in opposition to, the beliefs,
8 affiliations, ideals, or principles identified in subdivision (1) of this
9 subsection.
10 (b) Nothing in subsection (a) of this section shall infringe on the ability of an applicant
11 for employment to voluntarily opine or speak regarding any matter, including matters of
12 contemporary political debate or social action.
13 (c) No application for employment shall inquire into matters prohibited as compelled
14 speech under this section.
15 (d) Nothing in this section shall be construed to:
16 (1) Prohibit discussion with or questions to an applicant regarding the content of
17 the applicant's resume, curriculum vitae, or other written work or oral remarks.
18 (2) Affect the ability of the prospective employing agency from complying with
19 applicable federal or State law, including employment oaths, appointment
20 affidavits, and licensure and certification requirements.
21 (3) Apply to speech protected by the First Amendment of the U.S. Constitution.
