21 SECTION 4. Article 10 of Chapter 143 of the General Statutes is amended by adding
22 a new section to read:
23 "§ 143-162.8. No public funds for discriminatory programs.
24 (a) No State agency, unit of local government, or non-State entity may use any State
25 funds or public monies to promote, support, fund, implement, or maintain discriminatory
26 programs. For the purposes of this section, a "discriminatory program" means a program
27 promoting the concepts listed in subsection (c) of G.S. 153A-100.1.
28 (b) No State agency, unit of local government, or non-State entity shall apply for, accept,
29 or utilize federal funds, grants, or other financial assistance that require compliance with
30 discriminatory programs. Any existing programs funded through such means shall be
31 discontinued unless continued participation is expressly required by federal law.
32 (c) The following definitions apply in this section:
33 (1) Non-State entity. – As defined in G.S. 143C-1-1.
34 (2) Public monies. – Funds from any source budgeted or expended by a local
35 political subdivision of the State, including, but not limited to, revenue
36 authorized by G.S. 153A-149 or G.S. 160A-209.
37 (3) State agency. – A unit of the executive, legislative, or judicial branch of State
38 government, such as a department, institution, division, commission, board,
39 council, community college, or The University of North Carolina system.
40 (4) State funds. – As defined in G.S. 143C-1-1. The term includes any monies
41 received or held by a constituent institution of The University of North
42 Carolina, including endowment funds as defined in G.S. 116-36 and
43 institutional trust funds as defined in G.S. 116-36.1.
44 (5) Unit of local government. – As defined in G.S. 143C-1-1.
45 (d) The prohibitions contained in subsections (a) and (b) of this section include, but are
46 not limited to, using State funds or public monies to do any of the following:
47 (1) Utilize discriminatory programs in employee hirings, trainings, or
48 promotions; admissions; or the awarding of contracts.
49 (2) Maintain offices or dedicated staff positions (whether permanent,
50 time-limited, full-time, part-time, or temporary) for discriminatory programs.
House Bill 799-First Edition Page 5

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (e) Nothing in this section shall be construed to conflict with, restrict, limit, or infringe
2 upon speech protected by the First Amendment of the U.S. Constitution.
3 (f) Nothing in this section shall be construed to conflict with or prohibit compliance with
4 Title IX of the Education Amendments of 1972, as amended; the Americans with Disabilities
5 Act, as amended; the Age Discrimination in Employment Act, as amended; Title VI of the Civil
6 Rights Act of 1964; or other applicable State or federal law.
7 (g) This section shall not be construed to apply to any of the following:
8 (1) Academic course instruction.
9 (2) Scholarly research or a creative work by an institution of higher education's
10 students, faculty, or other research personnel or the dissemination of that
11 research or work.
12 (3) An activity of a student organization registered with or recognized by an
13 institution of higher education.
14 (4) Guest speakers or performers on short-term engagements.
15 (5) A policy, practice, procedure, program, or activity to enhance student
16 academic achievement or postgraduate outcomes that is designed and
17 implemented without regard to race, sex, color, or ethnicity.
18 (6) Data collection.
19 (7) Bona fide qualifications based on sex which are reasonably necessary to the
20 normal operation of public higher education, including, but not limited to:
21 a. Sports teams organized by sex.
22 b. Single-sex bathrooms and locker rooms.
23 c. Requiring a maintenance employee assigned to a single-sex locker
24 room to be a member of that respective sex.
25 d. Fraternities and sororities restricted to members of one sex.
26 e. Having single-sex housing options for students.
27 (h) It is a Class 1 misdemeanor for a person to knowingly and willfully violate this
28 section.
29 (i) A violation of this section is subject to the applicable penalty provisions of Article 10
30 of Chapter 143C of the General Statutes, Article 11 of Chapter 159 of the General Statutes,
31 G.S. 143C-6-22, or G.S. 159-183.
32 (j) The State Auditor shall conduct periodic compliance audits to determine whether
33 there has been a violation of this section. If the State Auditor determines that a violation of this
34 section has occurred, the determination shall be referred for prosecution by the district attorney
35 of the county where all or a substantial part of the alleged violation occurred and reported to the
36 Joint Legislative Commission on Governmental Operations or the Local Government
37 Commission, as appropriate.
38 (k) Any person may bring a civil action for a violation of this section seeking injunctive
39 or declaratory relief and the recovery of reasonable attorneys' fees and costs. The civil action
40 shall be brought in the county in which all or a substantial part of the acts or omissions giving
41 rise to the action occurred.
42 (l) An employee of a State agency, unit of local government, or non-State entity may
43 bring a civil action for damages to the employee resulting from a violation of this section. The
44 civil action may be brought in the county where the employee resides or in which all or a
45 substantial part of the acts or omissions giving rise to the action occurred.
46 (m) The liability and penalty provisions contained in this section for violating its
47 provisions are in addition to, and not in lieu of, liability under any other applicable provision of
48 law or cause of action in consequence of the violation.
49 (n) The provisions of this section are severable. If any provision of this section or its
50 application is held invalid, that invalidity shall not affect other provisions or applications that can
51 be given effect without the invalid provision or application."
